One day, I hope that people do not need to go through the hoops that I have had to jump through to not be in pain 24/7. If they are, I want more professionals to know what to do.

Because my fellows, there ARE options. If the medicals know about them.

💛

10/10

I mean isn't that a good fucking question? I now am acutely aware of just how high my pain tolerance is. My body is RIDDLED with problems and yet here I am.

But it shouldn't be that way. I wish more doctors were like him. Which is why #EndometriosisAwarenessMonth exists 9/10

Now? I've dropped 4 stone knowing that this illness would require more surgery.

As of this morning I've been told I'll need potentially a full hysterectomy and bowel surgery at the same time. 

My doctor asked: Why has nobody ever given you any pain relief? 8/?

Surgery happened! 2017 is the year I speak of nearly dying twice. 

I won't elaborate any further as to why.

The sent me home with anti-sick meds and told me to take pain relief. After open surgery.

The receptionists were cold and I actually never heard again. 7/?

I got referred to London. A really cold and uncaring place if you ask me today. 

One time they rang me and asked me why I wasn't at my surgery. 

They mixed up the dates.

Another, I sat for 33 hours without food and my surgery was cancelled. 

6/?

The doctor at the hospital was sweet, but told me I might have cancer. But likely had endometriosis and fibroids. 

I cried on the bench outside. My coworker came to help me drive home. 

5/?

Just after that, I ended up going back to my GP. This time my abdomen felt really hard. Infact, it had felt that way since I could remember, since June maybe? Who knows, life was such a whirlwind at the time I said.

My GP: You've got cysts, time to get a referral 4/?

Months later, down in October, I couldn't pee. I ended up in A&E. Who had literally no idea what was wrong. I was "too young" for these symptoms. 

I had a catheter for two weeks and then...sort of forgot about that too. 3/?

In June 2016, I was celebrating my birthday with my parents. Just after eating I had pain so bad in my abdomen that I thought I needed am ambulance. I thought maybe it was the sushi has made me ill. 

I brushed off the hour long pain and forgot about it 2/?

I vague post a lot about what is going on with me. I think over the years many people have been able to piece it together. Today, on the first day of #EndometriosisAwarenessMonth and off the back of a private appointment, I'd like to just give the void something 1/?

And in conclusion to my 5am rant about how messed up things are. 

Be kind to one another. Battles are being fought silently every single day.

The only things I have of her are one photo and her eternity ring and those things are priceless.

I'm grateful to my dad for sharing what he can when he's able too and for my step-mum for being there for all of us.

Mum, I wish I could take back the time that was stolen from us

I spend a lot of time missing a woman I look like, but truly know very little about.

What was her favourite ice cream? What did her laugh sound like.

Fuck, what was her voice even like? 

Do you see?

I was three when my mother passed away. Whilst I was never lied too (like Harry) about my mother, it's taken a very very long time to find out even remotely anything about her. 

It's painful for folks/family to discuss her because she died in pain and suffered greatly.

Harry then spends the next seven years trying to find out more about his parents whilst simultaneously being told:

You have your mother's eyes.

That fucking kills me every time. Because I was always told:

You have your mother's smile.

How do I feel about this? 

Well the best, recent example I have is actually Harry potter (can you tell I watched it recently?)

Harry lost his parents when he was a baby. Thinking they were killed in a car crash.

It took until he was 11 to find out otherwise

I see it pop up, more often that not in the news. 

Baby was too young to remember. So at least they have that.

But what folks don't really understand is it messes with you in a completely different way.

So in true fashion of our brains, I spent a lot of time thinking about my previous tweet. 

When a parent dies, it obviously has a profound movement in their child. (Speaking as if guardian/child relationship was a good one). 

But what if that child was a baby?

Each year I get to find out more and more about my mum. 

Today I found out a bit more and my heartbreaks a little more each time. 

I miss her deeply. But it never feels fair to overwhelm my dad with questions.

I cut that story really short, because Twitter, but know that a lot of you out there who have battled with awful illnesses gave me a lot of courage this week. That just because a doctor says so, doesn't always mean that's the right course for you.

and this time. I didn't get a no, it was ok, let's move this forward when you're ready.

Its a life changing operation, both literally and mentally. I'll never be able to have my own children, but maybe, after 4 years, I'm getting somewhere? 

7/7

It sounds a bit daft, but I've seen so many of you in the #endometriosis community and #chronicillness pushing back on things that I decided to go back and ask this doctor for help. 

Give me my surgery. Please. 

6/?

I decided to start looking into private care. I know some of the Americans will think this isn't much, but I was looking at over £7000 to have this surgery done privately.

I mean, who has that lying around? Not me. 5/?

I'm 29, so most doctors, whether I agree or not, are worried about performing such a major surgery on someone "so young". 

I'd not really had any resistance before on it, until a week or so ago. 

I was devastated. 4/?

The doctor who I'm now in the care of is nice, but lay down news I already knew.

Either leave it alone

or

Have a hysterectomy. 

Hoo boy, that's heavy news. 

3/?

About a month ago I felt a hard lump in my abdonmen. More fibroids. (waddup my #endometriosis #fibroids carrying humans). 

Long story short I was put back into the NHS system (after open surgery to remove others in 2017). 2/?

Can I share something a little personal? That's good news? 

Great. Let's go. 1/?
